1191000 1100000 198000000 990 10513000 21001000 1900000 2400000 13793100 200000 61000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Beneficial conversion feature</font><font style="display: inline;"> &#x2013; The issuance of our Series A preferred stock generated a beneficial conversion feature, which arises when a debt or equity security is issued with an embedded conversion option that is beneficial to the investor or in the money at inception because the conversion option has an effective strike price that is less than the market price of the underlying stock at the commitment date. We recognized the beneficial conversion feature by allocating the intrinsic value of the conversion option</font><font style="display: inline;">, which is the number of </font><font style="display: inline;">shares </font><font style="display: inline;">of common stock </font><font style="display: inline;">available upon conversion multiplied by the difference between the effective conversion price per share and the fair value of common stock per share on the commitment date, to additional paid-in capital, resulting in a discount on the Se</font><font style="display: inline;">ries A preferred stock. We are accreting</font><font style="display: inline;"> the discount </font><font style="display: inline;">over eight years </font><font style="display: inline;">from the date of issuance through the redemption date. Accretion expense will be recognized as dividend equivalents over the eight year period utilizing the effective interest method.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 7400000 2500000 7300000 2300000 100000 100000 37870000 37870000 108148000 108148000 29.00 14.50 5176000 5259000 6940000 3964000 75000 2015-12-01 2014-10-01 15800000 2612000 583000 6 12600000 1600000 1600000 3800000 12565000 15839000 4100000 4100000 0 0 140455000 170045000 3500000 1500000 2000000 2000000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">16\. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We and certain current and former officers and directors were named as defendants in complaints filed by investors in the United States District Cour</font><font style="display: inline;">t for the District of Colorado.</font><font style="display: inline;">The first complaint was filed in November 2007 and several other complaints were filed shortly thereafter. These actions were consolidated and, in September 2008, the district court appointed a lead plaintiff and counsel. An amended consolidated complaint was filed in December 2008. The amended complaint purported to state claims under Sections&nbsp;10(b), 20(a), and 20A of the Exchange Act on behalf of a class of all persons who purchased our common stock between April&nbsp;2, 2007 and April&nbsp;14, 2008 (the "Class Period"). The amended complaint also added our independent auditor as a defendant. The amended complaint alleged that, during the Class Period, the defendants made false and misleading public statements about us and our business and prospects and, as a result, the market price of our common s</font><font style="display: inline;">tock was artificially inflated. </font><font style="display: inline;">The amended complaint also claimed that certain current and former officers and directors traded in our common stock on the basis of material non-public information. The amended complaint sought compensatory damages on behalf of the alleged class in an unspecified amount, including interest, and also sought attorneys' fees and costs of litigation. On February&nbsp;28, 2011, the District Court granted motions to dismiss filed by the defendants and dismissed all claims. A final judgment was thereafter entered. Plaintiffs subsequently appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit. We and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants entered into a Stipulation of Settlement with the plaintiffs to resolve all claims asserted against us by the plaintiffs on behalf of the putative class. Our independent auditor was not a party to the Stipulation of Settlement. The Stipulation of Settlement received preliminary approval from the District Court on August&nbsp;28, 2013. On September 18, 2014, the District Court entered an order of final approval of the settlement and, on September 19, 2014, the District Court entered final judgment dismissing the action against us and those current and form</font><font style="display: inline;">er officers and directors named as defendants in its entirety with prejudice. </font><font style="display: inline;">The full settlement amount </font><font style="display: inline;">has been paid by our insurers. </font><font style="display: inline;">Since no notice of appeal was filed during the appeal period, the settlement will become final on or about October 30, 2014.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We are currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs &amp; Border Protection (&#x201C;CBP&#x201D;) in respect of</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> the period from 2006 to 2010. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In October 2013, CBP issued a revised final audit report.&nbsp;In that report CBP projects that unpaid duties totaling approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">12.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million are due for the period under review (a reduction from $14.3 million in the preliminary</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> draft report issued in 2012). </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We have responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter is consider</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ably less than the projection. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">It is not possible at this time to predict whether our arguments will be successful in eliminating or reducing the amount in dispute.&nbsp;&nbsp;CBP has stated that the final report will recommend</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> collection of the duties due. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">At this time, it is not possible to determine precisely when a notice of claim will be received from CBP, but currently we anticipate a notice of claim could be rec</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">eived </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">sometime in the first quarter of 2015</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Like</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">wise, it is not possible to predict with any certainty whether CBP will seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any unpaid duties, but such an assertion is a possibility.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Mexico&#x2019;s Federal Tax Authority (&#x201C;SAT&#x201D;) audited the period f</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">rom January 2006 to July 2011. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">There were two phases to the audit, the first for capital equipment and finished goods and</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> the second for raw materials.&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The first phase was completed and no major discrepancies</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> were noted by the SAT.&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On January 9, 2013, Crocs received a notice for the second phase in which the SAT issued a tax assessment (taxes and penalties) of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">280.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">22.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million) based on the value of all of Crocs&#x2019; imported raw mate</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">rials during the audit period.&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We believe that the proposed penalty amount is unfounded and without merit. With the help of local counsel we filed an appeal by t</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">he deadline of March 15, 2013.&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We have argued that the amount due in connection with the matter, if any, is substantially less </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">than that proposed by the SAT.&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In connection with the appeal, the SAT required us to post an appeal surety bond in the amount of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">321.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">26.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million), which amount reflects estimated additional penalties and interest if we are</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> not successful on our appeal.&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">This amount will </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">be adjusted on an annual basis. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We expect it to take between two and three years for resolution of this matter in th</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e Mexican courts. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter or reasonably estimate any potential loss.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, we have accrued a to</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">tal of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$4.2</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million relat</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ing to these litigati</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">on matters and other disputes. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We estimate that the ultimate resolution of these litigation matters and other disputes could result in a loss that is reasonably possible between </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$0.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million a</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nd </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$9.6</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million in th</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">e aggregate, in excess of the amount accrued.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Although we are subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, we are not party to any other pending legal proceedings that we believe would reasonably have a material adverse impact on our business, financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 100 75 182200000 209000 6050000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">9</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;">REVOLVING CREDIT FACILITY&nbsp;&amp; BANK BORROWINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On </font><font style="display: inline;">December 16, 2011</font><font style="display: inline;">, we entered into a</font><font style="display: inline;">n Amended and Restated Credit Agreement</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">(</font><font style="display: inline;">as amended,</font><font style="display: inline;"> the &#x201C;Credit Agreement&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;"> with the lenders named therein and P</font><font style="display: inline;">NC Bank, National Association (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">PNC</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x201D;</font><font style="display: inline;">), as a lender and admini</font><font style="display: inline;">strative agent for the lenders. </font><font style="display: inline;">The Credit Agreement enables us to borrow up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$100.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, with the ability to increase commitments to up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$125.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, subject to certain conditions, and is currently set to mature in December 2017. The Credit Agreement is available for working capital, capital expenditures, permitted acquisitions, reimbursement of drawings under letters of credit, and permitted dividends, distributions, purchases, redemptions and retirements of equity interests. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of our assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On September 26, 2014, we entered into the Fifth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (the &#x201C;Fifth Amendment&#x201D;), pursuant to which certain terms of the Credit Agreement were amen</font><font style="display: inline;">ded. The Fifth Amendment primarily (i) extend</font><font style="display: inline;">s the minimum fixed charge coverage ratio of 1.15 to 1.00 through the second quarter of 2015 and will return to 1.25 to 1.00 for each quarter thereafter, and (ii) amends certain definitions of the financial covenants to become more favorable to us.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">we had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outs</font><font style="display: inline;">tanding borrowings under</font><font style="display: inline;"> the Credit Agreement. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">, we had issued and outstanding letters of cred</font><font style="display: inline;">it </font><font style="display: inline;">of $</font><font style="display: inline;">8.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million an</font><font style="display: inline;">d $</font><font style="display: inline;">7.2</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms o</font><font style="display: inline;">f the </font><font style="display: inline;">Credit Agreement. As of </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;">, we were in compliance with all restrictive and financial covenants under the Credit Agreement.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Long-term Bank Borrowings </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">On December&nbsp;10, 2012, we entered into a Master </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">Installment Payment Agreement (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">Master IPA</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&#x201D;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">)</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> with PNC in which PNC finances our </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">purchase of software and services, which may include but are not limited to third party costs to design, install and implement software systems, and associated hardware described in the schedules defined within the Master IPA. Th</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">e Master IPA</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> was entered into to finance our implementation of a new enterprise resource p</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">lanning (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">ERP</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&#x201D;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">) system</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> which began in October 2012 and is estimated to continue through </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">early 2015</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">. The terms of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">each note payable under the Master IPA</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> consist of variable interest rates and payment terms based on amounts borrowed and timing of activity throughout the implementation of the ERP system.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;background-color:yellow;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> separate notes payable</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> under the Master IPA, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">whic</font><font style="display: SERIES A PREFERRED STOCK</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">On January&nbsp;27, 2014, we issued to </font><font style="display: inline;">Blacks</font><font style="display: inline;">tone Capital Partners VI&nbsp;L.P. (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">Blackstone</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x201D;</font><font style="display: inline;">)</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">, and certain of its permitted transferees (together with Blackstone, the &#x201C;Blackstone Purchasers&#x201D;), 200,000 shares of our Series&nbsp;A preferred stock for an aggregate purchase price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$198.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">&nbsp;million, or </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$990</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> per share, pursuant to an Investment Agreement between us and Blackstone, dated December&nbsp;28, 2013 (as amended, the &#x201C;Investment Agreement&#x201D;). In connection with the issuance of the Series A preferred stock (the &#x201C;Closing&#x201D;), we received proceeds of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$182.2</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million after deducting the issuance discount of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million and direct and incremental expenses of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$15.8</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million including financial advisory fees, closing costs, legal expenses and other offering-related expenses.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Participation Rights and </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Dividends</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">The Series&nbsp;A preferred stock ranks senior to our common stock with respect to dividend rights and rights on liquidation, winding-up and dissolution. The Series&nbsp;A preferred stock has a stated value of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$1,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per share, and holders of Series&nbsp;A preferred stock are entitled to cumulative dividends payable quarterly in cash at a rate of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">6%</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per annum. If we fail to make timely dividend payments, the dividend rate will increase to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">8%</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per annum until such time as all accrued but unpaid dividends have been paid in full. Holders of Series&nbsp;A preferred stock are entitled to receive dividends declared or paid on our common stock and are entitled to vote together with the holders of our common stock </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">as a single class, in each case, on an as-converted basis. As of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">, we have</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> accrued dividends of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$3.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">1</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> million on the condensed consolidated balance sheets, which were paid in cash to Blackstone on </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">October 1</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">, 2014. Holders of Series&nbsp;A preferred stock have c</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">ertain limited special approval rights, including with respect to the issuance of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">pari passu</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> or senior equity securities of the Company.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Conversion Features</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">The Series&nbsp;A preferred stock is convertible at the option of the holders at any time after the Closing into shares of common stock at an implied conversion price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$14.50</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per share, subject to adjustment. At our election, all or a portion of the Series&nbsp;A preferred stock will be convertible into the relevant number of shares of common stock on or after the third anniversary of the Closing, if the closing price of the common stock equals or exceeds </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$29.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> for 20 consecutive trading days. The Series A preferred stock is convertible into </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">13,793,100</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> shares of our common stock based on the conversio</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">n rate in place</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. Upon certain change of control events involving us, the holders can require us to repurchase the Series&nbsp;A preferred stock at 101% of the stated value thereof plus all accrued but unpaid dividends. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">In accordance with FASB ASC Topic 480-10-S99-3A, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">SEC Staff Announcement: Classification and Measurement of Redeemable Securities</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">, redemption features which are not solely within the control of the issuer are required to be presented outside of permanent equity on the condensed consolidated balance sheets. Under the Investment Agreement and as noted above, the holder has the option to redeem the Series A preferred stock any time after January 27, 2022 or upon a change in control. As such, the Series A preferred stock is presented in temporary or mezzanine equity on the condensed consolidated balance sheets and will be accreted up to the stated redemption value of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$203.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> million using an appropriate accretion method over a redemption period of eight year</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s, as this represents the earliest proba</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ble date at which the Series A preferred s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">tock will become redeemable</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 14.76 14.74 false \--12-31 Q3 2014 2014-09-30 10-Q 0001334036 82496973 Large Accelerated Filer Crocs, Inc. crox 11942000 17196000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">5\. COMMITMENTS &amp; CONTINGENCIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Rental Commitments and Contingencies</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We rent space for certain of our retail stores, offices, warehouses, vehicles, and equipment under operating leases expiring at various dates thro</font><font style="display: inline;">u</font><font style="display: inline;">gh 2033.</font><font style="display: inline;"> &nbsp;C</font><font style="display: inline;">ertain leases contain rent escalation clauses (step rents) that require additional rental amounts in the later years of the term. Rent expense for leases with step rents or rent holidays is recognized on a straight-line basis over the lease term. Deferred rent is included in the </font><font style="display: inline;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;">c</font><font style="display: inline;">onsolidated balance sheets in a</font><font style="display: inline;">ccrued expenses</font><font style="display: inline;"> and other current liabilities.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 814000 1025000 32424000 5158000 3888000 2071000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">8</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">. DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We transact business in various foreign countries and are therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. We have entered into foreign currency exchange forward contract</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and currency swap derivative instruments to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreign currency exchange rates. We do not designate these derivative instruments as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging. Accordingly, these instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value rec</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ognized in &#x2018;Forei</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">gn currency transaction </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">losses, net&#x2019; in our condensed consolidated statements of income. For purposes of the condensed consolidated statement</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> of cash flows, we classify the cash flows at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged items, generally within &#x2018;Cash provided by (used in) operating activities&#x2019;. See</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;"> Note 7</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;"> &#x2013; Fair Value Measurements</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> for further details regarding the fair values of the corresponding derivative assets and liab</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ilities.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign currency exchange contracts at </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nited States (&#x201C;U.S.&#x201D;) D</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily rep</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">resent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of our exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </tr> </table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restricted Stock Awards and Units</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">From time to time, we grant </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">restricted stock awards (&#x201C;RSA&#x201D;) and restricted stock units (&#x201C;RSU&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to our </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">employees. R</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">SAs and RSUs </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">generally vest over three or four years depending on the terms of the grant.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Unvested RSAs have the same rights as those of common shares including voting rights and non-forfeitable dividend rights. However, ownership of unvested RSAs cannot be transferred until they are ve</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">sted. An unvested RSU is a contractual right to receive a share of common stock only upon its vesting. RSUs have dividend equivalent rights which accrue over the term of the award and are paid if and when the RSUs vest, but they have no voting rights.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">We typically grant time-based RSUs and performance-based RSUs. Time-based RSUs are typically granted on an annual basis to certain non-executive employees and vest in three annual installments on a straight-line basis beginning one year after the grant date. During the </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">2013</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">, the board of directors </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">did not approve the grant of a material amount o</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">f</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">time-based RSUs to non-executives. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">During the </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">nine</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per share</font><font style="display: inline;"> \- Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. Our recently issued Series A </font><font style="display: inline;">convertible </font><font style="display: inline;">preferred stock </font><font style="display: inline;">(&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) </font><font style="display: inline;">represent</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of our non-vested restricted stock awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in our earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above, which assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Note 12&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">12</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. Share repurchases may be made in the open market or in privately negotiated transactions. The repurchase authorization does not have an expiration date and does not oblige us to acquire any particular amount of our common stock. Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of our non-financial instrument assets</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Inventory Write-down </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: the </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">nine</font><font charges, with the remaining amounts reported in cost of sales in the condensed consolidated statements of income. These charges were related to certain obsolete footwear in our Americas operating segment as well as Corporate.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 154272000 197213000 162341000 202819000 7384000 5317000 685000 289000 896000 1676000 853000 1304000 424000 93235000 97697000 7200000 8200000 250415000 258657000 875159000 1006932000 186928000 220316000 0 100000000 125000000 4200000 16800000 12900000 11670000 7714000 5100000 5200000 1296000 1610000 4765000 5271000 9600000 0 52003000 52737000 -3858000 83527000 -54054000 -44829000 94309000 -5295000 77353000 13036000 48168000 15767000 77353000 13036000 37905000 12009000 4 105976000 36679000 206132000 -14907000 61787000 76478000 31188000 45000 -85294000 17907000 11656000 50175000 -5495000 17969000 13690000 6860000 15000 -26788000 59846000 29421000 178088000 -13750000 53451000 65962000 29254000 45000 -104537000 1113000 9091000 38258000 -5405000 15094000 4384000 9689000 15000 -31755000 15240000 5596000 14635000 4952000 75093000 26047000 82307000 26629000 89864000 31485000 96206000 31320000 469000 158000 736000 261000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1\. GENERAL</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Organization</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. and its subsidiaries (collectively the &#x201C;Company,&#x201D; &#x201C;we,&#x201D; &#x201C;our&#x201D; or &#x201C;us&#x201D;) are engaged in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing and distribution of footwear, apparel and accessories for men, women and children.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Basis of Presentation</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) for interim financial information and with the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;) for reporting on Form&nbsp;10-Q. The condensed consolidated balance sheet as of December 31, 2013 was derived from the Company&#x2019;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2013 (the &#x201C;2013 Form 10-K&#x201D;). Accordingly, these statements do not include all of the information and disclosures required by GAAP or SEC rules&nbsp;and regulations for complete financial statements. In the opinion of management, these financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair presentation of the results for the interim periods presented. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Reclassifications</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Certain prior period amounts on the condensed consolidated financial statements have been reclassified to conform to current period presentation. We segregated </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million in restructuring charges recorded to cost of sales on the condensed consolidated statements of income and inventory write-down charges on the condensed consolidated statements of cash flows during the three months ended June 30, 2014 to the restructuring charges line item in cost of sales on the condensed consolidated statements of income during the </font><font style="display: inline;">nine</font><font style="display: inline;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;">. In addition, we reclassified </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million of asset impairment charges recorded to other non-cash items on the condensed consolidated statements of cash flows during the nine months ended September 30, 2013 to the asset impairment charges line item on the condensed consolidated statements of cash flows during the nine months ended September 30, 2013 to conform to the current year presentation. These reclassifications had no effect on income from operations or cash provided by (used in) operating activities.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">These </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">condensed consolidated financial </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">statements should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and footnotes included in the 2013 Form 10-K. The accounting policies used in preparing these unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements are the same as those described in </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Note 1 &#x2014; Organization &amp; Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to the consolidated financial statements in the 2013 Form 10-K.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Earnings per share</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> \- Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. Our recently issued Series A </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">convertible </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">preferred stock </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">(&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">represent</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of our non-vested restricted stock awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in our earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above, which assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Note 12&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Beneficial conversion feature</font><font style="display: inline;"> &#x2013; The issuance of our Series A preferred stock generated a beneficial conversion feature, which arises when a debt or equity security is issued with an embedded conversion option that is beneficial to the investor or in the money at inception because the conversion option has an effective strike price that is less than the market price of the underlying stock at the commitment date. We recognized the beneficial conversion feature by allocating the intrinsic value of the conversion option</font><font style="display: inline;">, which is the number of </font><font style="display: inline;">shares </font><font style="display: inline;">of common stock </font><font style="display: inline;">available upon conversion multiplied by the difference between the effective conversion price per share and the fair value of common stock per share on the commitment date, to additional paid-in capital, resulting in a discount on the Se</font><font style="display: inline;">ries A preferred stock. We are accreting</font><font style="display: inline;"> the discount </font><font style="display: inline;">over eight years </font><font style="display: inline;">from the date of issuance through the redemption date. Accretion expense will be recognized as dividend equivalents over the eight year period utilizing the effective interest method.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Recently Adopted Accounting Standards</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">Discontinued Operations</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In April 2014, the </font><font style="display: inline;">Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#x201C;FASB&#x201D;) </font><font style="display: inline;">issued Accounting Standards Update (&#x201C;ASU&#x201D;) No. 2014-08: </font><font style="font-style:italic;display: inline;">Presentation of Financial Statements (Topic 205) and Property, Plant, and Equipment (Topic 360): Reporting Discontinued Operations and Disclosures of Disposals of Components of an Entity</font><font style="display: inline;">, which amends the definition of a discontinued operation in ASC 205-20 and requires entities to provide additional disclosures about discontinued operations as well as disposal transactions th</font><font style="display: inline;">at do not meet the discontinued </font><font style="display: inline;">operations criteria. The FASB issued the ASU to provide more decision-useful information and to make it more difficult for a disposal transaction to qualify as a discontinued operation. Under the previous guidance, the results of operations of a component of an entity were classified as a discontinued operation if all of the following conditions were met:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">The component has been disposed of or is classified as held for sale.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">The operations and cash flows of the component have been (or will be) eliminated from the ongoing operations of the entity as a result of the disposal transaction.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">The entity will not have any significant continuing involvement in the operations of the component after the disposal transaction.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The new guidance eliminates the second and third criteria above and instead requires discontinued operations treatment for disposals of a component or group of components that represents a strategic shift that has or will have a major impact on an entity&#x2019;s operations or financial results. The ASU also expands the scope of ASC 205-20 to disposals of equity method investments and businesses that, upon initial acquisition, qualify as held for sale. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In addition, the ASU requires entities to reclassify assets and liabilities of a discontinued operation for all comparative periods presented in the statement of financial position. Before these amendments, ASC 205-20 neither required nor prohibited such presentation.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Regarding the statement of cash flows, an entity must disclose, in all periods presented, either (1) operating and investing cash flows or (2) depreciation and amortization, capital expenditures, and significant operating and investing noncash items related to the discontinued operation. This presentation requirement represents a significant change from previous guidance. This ASU is effective pro</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">spectively for all disposals or components initially classified as held for sale in periods beginning on or after December 15, 2014. Early adoption is permitted. The adoption of this pronouncement did not have a material impact to the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Recently Issued Accounting Standards</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">Going Concern</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On August 27, 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-15, which provides guidance on determining when and how reporting entities must disclose going concern uncertainties in their financial statements. The new standard requires management to perform interim and annual assessments of an entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year of the date of issuance of the entity&#x2019;s financial statements (or within one year after the date on which the financial statements are available to be issued, when applicable). Further, an entity must provide certain disclosures if there is &#x201C;substantial doubt about the entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The FASB believes that requiring management to perform the assessment will enhance the timeliness, clarity and consistency of related disclosures and improve convergence with IFRSs (which emphasize management&#x2019;s responsibility for performing the going concern assessment). However, the time horizon for the assessment (look-forward period) and the disclosure thresholds under U.S. GAAP and IFRSs will continue to differ. This ASU is effective for annual periods ending after December 16, 2016, and interim periods thereafter; early adoption is permitted. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Company does not believe that</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> this pronouncement </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">will</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> have a material impact to the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">Share-Based Payment</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On June 19, 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Company does not believe that</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> this pronouncement </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">will</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> have a material impact to the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; In applying the revenue model to contracts within its scope, an entity:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xB7; Identifies the contract(s) with a customer (Step 1)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xB7; Identifies the performance obligations in the contract (Step 2)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xB7; Determines the transaction price (Step 3)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xB7; Allocates the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract (Step 4)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-indent: -18pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&#xB7; Recognizes revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a performance obligation (Step 5)</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <a name="PB_6_160358_8146"></a><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The ASU applies to all contracts with customers except those that are within the scope of other topics in the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Certain of the ASU&#x2019;s provisions also apply to transfers of nonfinancial assets, including in-substance nonfinancial assets that are not an output of an entity&#x2019;s ordinary activities (e.g., sales of property, plant, and equipment, real estate or intangible assets). Existing accounting guidance applicable to these transfers has been amended or superseded. Compared with current U.S. GAAP, the ASU also requires significantly expanded disclosures about revenue recognition.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The ASU is effective for annual reporting periods (including interim reporting periods within those periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. Early application is not permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial statements.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 6513000 10673000 53661000 34220000 -3000 0 0 0 4537000 -6030000 19650000 18891000 15201000 15685000 -865000 170000 -180000 -13000 388000 217000 4484000 1776000 276000 41000 5229000 1684000 12533000 90093000 -8609000 -1335000 -7092000 -182000 5166000 0 15800000 256000 787000 22665000 29457000 30753000 13891000 8233000 3067000 0.001 0.001 5000000 5000000 0 0 29175000 36717000 2017000 1300000 182220000 18568000 551000 174000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">3\. PROPERTY &amp; EQUIPMENT</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table summarizes property and equipment by major classification as of </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">:</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <tr> <td valign="bottom" Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;"> &nbsp;</p> </td> </tr> <tr> <td valign="bottom" style="width:50.62%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;overflow: hidden;font-size:0pt;"> &nbsp;</p> </td> <td colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="width:00.02%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:center;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 8pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:8pt;">September 30,</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:02.82%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:12.75pt;padding:0pt;"> <p RESTRUCTURING ACTIVITIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:4.5pt 0pt 0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restructuring</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;background-color:yellow;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On July 21, 2014, we announced strategic plans for long-term improv</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ement and growth of the business. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">These plans comprise four</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> key initiatives including: (1) s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">treamlining the global product and marketing portfolio, (2) reducing direct investment in smaller geographic markets, (3) creating a more efficient organizational structure including reducing duplicative and excess overhead which will also enhance the decision making process, and (4) closing or converting approx</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">imately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">75</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">100</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> retail location</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s around the world.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> The initial effects of these plans were incurred in the first quarter of 2014 and are expected to continue through 2015. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The Company recorded re</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">structuring charges of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$8.2</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$16.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million during the </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nine</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, respectively. We are unable in good faith to determine the type of costs we will incur in connection with this strategic restructuring plan or to estimate the total amount or range of amounts expected to be incurred in connection with this plan for each major type of cost associated with this strategic restructuring plan.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As mentioned above, the Company plans to close 75 to 100 retail locations around the globe. As such, we expect to incur certain exit costs specific to store closures including operating lease termination costs, rent obligations for leased facilities, net of expected sublease income, and other expenses in association with this plan. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nine</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> months ended </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, we clos</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ed 26 and 36 co</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">mpany-operated </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">retail locations, respectively, which were not scheduled to close until future periods and were selected for closure by management based on historical and projected profitability levels, relocation plans, and other factor</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s. As of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">September 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, we recorded a liability of appro</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$1.1</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million rela</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ted to these locations in accrued restructuring on the condensed consolidated balance sh</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">eet. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The calculation of accrued store closing reserves primarily includes future minimum lease payments from the date of closure to the end of the remaining lease term, net of contractual or estimated sublease income.
